        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>This is a ToO observation of a point source (SN) aiming at detection early mm-wave synchrotron emission. Thus we require maximum sensitivity and we choose a continuum wide-band correlator mode. 
The choise of frequency is based on optimazation of sensitivity required, on-source time to achive this sensitivity and contamination from possible molecular lines. We thus choose 100 GHz as our observing frequency. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>This is ToO observation of a point source (SN) and thus it will not be resolved with ALMA. 
In order to localize the SN within its host galaxy and optimally separate any SN emission from other possible host agalxy emission, we request a resolution of 0.5" or better (if possible). However, due to the time constraint of this ToO, a worse resolution is also acceptable and thus the observation can be undertaken in any array configuration. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>This is a ToO observation in search for early short-lived mm-wave emission from flash spectroscopy SNe. This is the first time such an attempt is presued. Based on the optical spectra of such SNe, the CSM denstieis and the extent of the CSM, we expected emission at the level of 0.1 mJy or above (up to 1 mJy at best). The emission is expected ot tuen on 2 - 3 days after SN explsion and to turn off after ~ 10 days. Since this is basically a "detection" experiment of a point source, we require continuum observation for maximum sensitivity. Taking into acount a 10 sigma detection we require a 10 micro Jy sensitivity.


</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The mm-wave emission we search for is a result of interaction of the SN ejecta with a thin CSM shell. The interaction is expected to produce mm-wave emission in the first day after the SN explosion and up to 10 days (when the CSM shell is swept away and the interaction stops). Our optical survey is capable of discovering SNe hours after they explode. The confirmation process takes a few more hours. The ALMA ToO is expected to be submitted 12 hours after the SN explosion. The 48 hours ALMA turn around time is expected to provide the initial ALMA observation when the SN is ~3 days old. Three followup observations are expected to follow with separations of 48 hours to trace the evolution of the mm-wave emission and eventually to detect its rapid decline towards the end of the SN-CSM interaction (about 10 days after SN explosion). </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_TIME_CONSTRAINT</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
